Chem., 2021, 19, 5888–5898 The inverting mechanism of the metal ion-independent LanGT2: the ﬁrst step to understand the glycosylation of natural product antibiotic precursors through QM/MM simulations† Glycosyltransferases (GTs) from the GT1 family are responsible for the glycosylation of various important organic structures such as terpenes, steroids and peptide antibiotics, making it one of the most intensely studied families of GTs. The target of our study, LanGT2, is a member of the GT1 family that uses an inverting mechanism for transferring olivose from TDP-olivose, the donor substrate, to the natural product tetrangulol (Tet), the precursor of the antibiotic landomycin A. X-ray crystallography in conjunc- tion with mutagenesis experiments has revealed the catalytic signiﬁcance of 3 amino acids (Ser10, Ser219 and Asp137), suggesting Asp137 as the base catalyst. In the absence of X-ray structures that include the

acceptor substrate Tet, in silico experiments and MD simulations that have modeled ternary complexes propose that Asp137 could recruit a water molecule to facilitate the nucleophilic activation of Tet, since the distance between Asp137 and the nucleophile is too long to directly deprotonate the nucleophilic moiety. So far, there is no computational evidence regarding the precise mechanism by which LanGT2 catalyzes the transfer of olivose, which raises questions such as: is a water-assisted mechanism possible? and how does this metal ion-independent GT stabilize the growing negative charge of the diphosphate leaving group? In this work, the QM/MM approach was used to unravel the catalytic mechanism of LanGT2, and to identify the role of crucial catalytic amino acids at a molecular level. Our calculations show that the minimum energy path (MEP) describes an SN2-like mechanism, identifying an oxocarbe- nium ion-like TS in which the olivosyl moiety adopts a 4H3 conformation. Interactions established between the diphosphate group of TDP and Ser10, Ser219, Arg220 and His283 are key to stabilize the development of charge on the leaving group. Our work also suggests that a water-mediated proton trans- fer mechanism is feasible, in which the water molecule is key to stabilize the phenolate ion-like nucleo- phile in the TS. This is the ﬁrst computational insight into the inverting mechanism of an antibiotic natural product GT, and its implications may serve to guide the design of new biocatalysts for natural product glycodiversiﬁcation.

Glycosylated structures are involved in, or directly carry out, a myriad of functions, ranging from energy storage to cellular recognition and immune responses.1 Natural products (NPs) with antibiotic or anticancer activities are appreciated pharmaceutical resources, and the attachment of sugar residues to the structures of these small natural aromatic compounds (or NPs) is typically essen- tial for their biological activity.1,2 In fact, the identity of the monosaccharide, as well as the regio- and stereospecific linkage of the sugar moiety attached to the NP, can modulate both the pharmacokinetics and the biological specificity of the metabolite;2,3 thus the sugar moiety can impact the aﬃnity of This journal is © The Royal Society of Chemistry 2021 Organic & Biomolecular Chemistry a metabolite for a given target, and the in vivo properties of the NP.4,5 These roles provide many possibilities for new bioactive substance exploitation, and have encouraged the progress of both chemical and enzymatic methods for the glycosylation of NPs.2 In the last case, the so-called promiscuous or engineered glycosyltransferases (GTs) from the GT1 family are noteworthy enzymes that have been used for altering the sugar moieties coupled to several NPs. This strategy has become a prominent method for redesigning NP structures with pharmacological applications.6,7

Glycosyltransferases (GTs) are the main enzymes respon- sible for the biosynthesis of new glycosidic bonds and, so far, they have been gathered into 113 sequence-based families, according to the CAZy database (May 6, 2021).8,9 GTs transfer a sugar moiety from an activated donor substrate, typically a nucleotide diphosphate (NDP) sugar, to a plethora of acceptor substrates such as other sugars, proteins, lipids, nucleic acids or NPs. When GTs catalyze glycosylation at O acceptor sites, they are commonly known as O-GTs, and give rise to O-glycosides (Fig. 1A). Although O-GTs are the most abundant in nature, N-, S- and C-GTs are also known, but to a lesser extent. Mechanistically, GTs can be classified as inverting or retaining enzymes based on the final stereochemistry of the anomeric the sugar being transferred (Fig. 1A). Natural product GTs from the GT1 family, like the enzyme that we present in this work, are known to catalyze inverting reactions (Fig. 1B) and have gained remarkable atten- tion over the last decade, since they have been used as biocata- lysts to modify glycosylated-NPs. This is mainly related to the fact that they exhibit a more flexible substrate specificity and regiospecificity, in comparison with most of the GTs, which synthesizing diﬀerent makes glycosides.1,2,10 Although the promiscuity of several wild-type Fig. 1 (A) GT catalyzed glycosyl group transfer with either inversion or retention of the anomeric stereochemistry with respect to the donor sugar (NMP refers to nucleoside mono-phosphate). (B) Classical SN2-like mechanism for inverting glycosylation (R1 can be a sugar, a lipid, a protein residue or a NP). This journal is © The Royal Society of Chemistry 2021

GTs from the GT1 family is often appropriate for proficient performance of enzyme-dependent approaches,11–14 the strin- gent substrate specificity of most GTs limits their synthetic applications. In this context, rational design of GTs, in which targeted mutations are guided by techniques like crystallogra- phy and computational simulations, has been proven to be a successful approach to overcome this obstacle.2 In addition to the promiscuity shown by some members of the GT1 family, another remarkable characteristic of these enzymes is their natural ability to catalyze the formation of C–C glycosidic bonds. C-Glycosides are of special interest for their unique bioactivity as well as for representing isosteric O-glycoside mimics that are stable against glycosidase degradation.15–17 In a mechanistic framework, the members of the GT1 family catalyze inverting reactions. These reactions are sup- posed to occur via a direct displacement SN2-like mechanism, assisted by a base catalyst that increases the nucleophilicity of the acceptor substrate. The mechanism involves the formation of an oxocarbenium-ion transition state (TS), and the base catalyst is provided by an active-site side chain, such as Asp, Glu or His (Fig. 1B). This mechanism has been supported by both experimental1,18,19 and theoretical studies.20–22 However, in some GTs a properly localized amino acid has not been found to exert the function of the catalytic base.23–27

Theoretical studies have shown that the cleavage of the acti- vated donor substrate, and the nucleophilic attack of the acceptor substrate to the anomeric carbon of the oxocarbe- nium ion-like transition state occurs almost simultaneously, whereas the base catalyst deprotonates the hydroxyl nucleophi- lic molecule (Fig. 1B).20–22,28 In this regard, some inverting GTs require a metal cofactor (Mn2+ or Mg2+) for their transfer- ase activity, which stabilizes the negative charge on the leaving group during the donor substrate breakage.19 This group of GTs is usually known as metal ion-dependent GTs. On the other hand, metal ion-independent GTs are proposed to use helix dipole and interactions with hydroxyl and imidazole groups to stabilize the development of the negative charge on the leaving group.19 inverting GTs that catalyze the glycosylation of sugars and Ser/Thr have been studied.21–23,28–30 However, theoretical studies of the glycosylation of aromatic compounds mediated by GT1 enzymes have been scarcely addressed at a molecular level, with the exception of a recent work on the glu- cosyltransferase UGT1 from the indigo plant Polygonum tinctorium.20 In this work, we studied the glycosylation of Tet catalyzed by the metal ion-independent O-GT LanGT2 (hereinafter O-LanGT2) from Streptomyces cyanogenus, which is a member of the GT1 family.31 O-LanGT2 transfers olivose from TDP- olivose (donor substrate) to the angucycline-based aglycon Tet. The glycosylation of Tet corresponds to the initial step in the biosynthesis of landomycin A, an antibiotic of the angucycline family.32 Interestingly, the structure of O-LanGT2 has been resolved with a chimeric variant (C-LanGT2),31,33 which can perform the C-glycosylation reaction using the same substrates as O-LanGT2. It is important to mention that based on the Org. Biomol. Chem., 2021, 19, 5888–5898 | 5889

crystal structures of O- and C-LanGT2,31 it has been proposed that both enzymes could employ a crystal water molecule to mediate the role of the base catalyst Asp137, which has been identified by visual inspection of crystal structures and muta- genesis experiments.34,35 In addition to Asp137, mutagenesis experiments have also pointed to the importance of Ser10 and Ser219, whose mutations completely abolished the transferase activity.34 Furthermore, MD simulation studies showed how residues Asp137, Ser10 and Ser219 formed key interactions with Tet (Asp137) and the donor substrate (Ser10 and Ser219), provid- ing a molecular interpretation of the catalytic roles of these residues.33 Despite having this important information, the exact catalytic roles of Ser10 and Ser219 in the reaction mecha- nism remain elusive. Thus, studying the mechanism of O-LanGT2 becomes relevant because it not only oﬀers an excel- lent opportunity to gain insights into the metal ion-indepen- dent enzyme catalysis, but also provides the molecular basis for the O-glycosylation mechanism of aromatic compounds. The implications of this new knowledge could be useful for understanding the C-glycosylation mechanism of the chimeric variant of O-LanGT2. Considering the previous antecedents, the key questions in examining the catalytic mechanism of O-LanGT2 are: (1) what is the catalytic role of Ser10? (2) what is the catalytic pathway, and could a water-mediated proton transfer mechanism acti- vate the aromatic nucleophile? and (3) how does the enzyme facilitate the departure of the diphosphate leaving group? In this study, we present QM/MM calculations aimed at providing the molecular details of the inverting mechanism catalyzed by O-LanGT2. Combining our previously acquired knowledge on this enzyme together with the QM/MM calculations, we achieved an in-depth understanding of the catalytic strategies that this key GT1 member uses to catalyze the glycosylation of an aromatic compound and, thus we have succeeded in unra- veling the inverting mechanism of O-LanGT2 and the role of specific active site residues, oﬀering a molecular interpretation of mutagenesis experiments.

Models and theoretical methods System Initial structural models of the ternary complex of O-LanGT2 were retrieved from our previous MD studies and, conse- quently the details of the MD procedures can be found in an earlier publication of our group.33 In any case, it is worth noting that two diﬀerent MD simulations of 200 ns allowed us to sample and build two diﬀerent models to evaluate the O-glycosylation mechanism. In model 1, the distance between Ser10 (hydrogen atom of the hydroxyl group, HS in Fig. 2) and the glycosidic oxygen (OG) was restrained to an equilibrium distance close to 2 Å along the MD simulations (red dotted line in model 1 at Fig. 2), whereas in model 2 there is no restraint on this distance. In the QM/MM approach the system is partitioned into quantum mechanics (QM) and molecular mechanics (MM) fragments. The changes of the QM part depend on the elec- tronic density, ρ(r), computed with density functional theory, whereas the MM fragment is described by force field methods. In this study, the first step was to select several snapshots from the previous MD simulations of models 1 and 2, ensuring that the distance C1–O8Tet is not longer than 4.5 Å. As the snap- shots corresponded to structures from the MD simulations, it was necessary to trim the solvation box to a sphere of 30 Å cen- tered at the carbon 1 (C1) of olivose (left panel at Fig. 2). The two QM/MM systems contain 9967 atoms and consider all protein residues. Both models were, then, partitioned into QM and MM layers. The first QM fragment (QM1) involves all atoms of Tet, a fraction of the donor substrate TDP-olivose, Asp137 and catalytic water Wcat, leading a total number of 80 atoms (including two capping hydrogens). The remaining 9875 atoms are part of the MM fragment. The acceptor substrate Tet was optimized while the rest of Ser10 (Fig. 3), and was explored with the goal to further assess the role of the residue Ser10 along the reaction path, which has been proven to be key in the catalytic activity.34 Since model 1 in conjunction with the QM2 zone yielded lower energetic barriers (Table S1†), the reaction path obtained in this way was used as a guessed reaction path to compute the minimum energy path (MEP). The MEP was calculated by (CPR) algorithm39 using the Conjugate peak refinement implemented in the TREK module of the CHARMM program. The CPR algorithm39 rebuilds the whole path that connects well minimized reactant and product structures, but we also provide several intermediate points of the initial reaction path. This sequence of structures is used to rebuild the path, result- ing in a path that follows the adiabatic energy valleys and has energy maxima that are true saddle points. Besides, only the energy function and its gradient are required, ensuring that the energy barrier is not aﬀected by a biasing description of the process. The CPR criterion for deciding whether a tran- −2 sition state has been found is that a gradient of less than 10 −1 is attained. All the refinements to obtain the kcal mol MEP were calculated through the QM(BP86/6-31G(d))/MM (CHARMM) method. The BP86 40–42 functional yields good results for structural parameters and it allows for fast optimi- zations, an important advantage especially when many diﬀerent probable starting structures have to be considered. The method has been used in several studies focused on reac- tions that involve the formation/breaking of glycosidic lin- kages; however, it is often necessary to correct the energies using more accurate methods such as hybrid or hybrid meta- GGA functionals.43–50 Thus, once the TS has been character- Org. The QM/MM calculations were carried out with the last implementation of QChem and the CHARMM program,51 using the QChem52 package for the description of the QM region. The molecular mechanics (MM) part was described using the Charmm36-all atoms force field.53–56 Electrostatic contributions This evaluation allows us to estimate the electrostatic contri- bution provided by distinct residues of the active site to the TS and product stabilizations, using as reference the reactant structure. This is done by incorporating these residues in the MM fragment and taking the diﬀerence in the QM energy term (including the QM-MM electrostatic interaction) when the residue has the force field assigned atomic charges and when those charges are set to 0. The electrostatic stabilization was evaluated at the QM(M06-2X/6-311G(d,p)/MM(CHARMM) level of theory in additional single-point energy calculations. A posi- tive electrostatic contribution value indicates that the enzyme residue can help stabilize the TS and product structures, suggesting that the residue binds more strongly the TS and product than the reactant structure. On the other hand, a negative electrostatic value suggests that the substrate–residue interaction is more favorable in the reactant structure. Perturbation theory energy analysis (PTEA) The stabilization energy associated with donor → acceptor delocalization was estimated by the PTEA method.57–59 This is carried out by exploring all possible interactions between the Lewis-type NBOs (donor) and non-Lewis-type NBOs (acceptor), estimating their energetic importance by 2nd-order pertur- bation theory. This analysis only looked at the QM region and the calculations were performed with the NBO 5.0 program,60 as implemented in the QChem package. The orbital represen- tations were generated with the Chemcraft program.61 Results and discussion Role of Ser10 during the transfer of olivose

In the present work, we have studied for the first time the enzymatic mechanism in which O-LanGT2 catalyzes the glyco- sylation of the natural product compound tetrangulol. As shown in Fig. 4, initially, two diﬀerent models were evaluated in order to determine the catalytic role of Ser10. In model 1, Ser10 closely interacts with the glycosidic oxygen (OG) of the donor substrate TDP-olivose (Fig. 4A), whereas in model 2 this interaction is not present (Fig. 4C). The diﬀerent reactant structures were used as starting points to carry out the initial explorations of the potential energy surface (PES). The most suitable reaction coordinate (rc) that drove the systems from reactant to product structures was rc = d1(ClOli–OG) − d2(ClOli– O8Tet) − d3(H8Tet–OW) − d4(O1Asp137–HW) (see Fig. 3 for labels). In this stage, models 1 and 2 were evaluated using the QM1 5892 | Org. Biomol. Chem., 2021, 19, 5888–5898 fragment, leading to potential energy profiles that showed diﬀerent energy barriers for the glycosylation reaction. In the case of model 1, the height of the energy barrier was 34 kcal −1 −1, whereas in the case of model 2 it was 54 kcal mol mol (Table S1†). Regarding the features of the highest energy struc- tures, model 1 exhibits an olivose⋯diphosphate (C1–OG) dis- tance of 2.56 Å (Fig. 4B), whereas in model 2 the C1–OG dis- tance is 2.28 Å (Fig. 4D). This seems to make room for the nucleophilic moiety to be located at 2.01 Å from the anomeric carbon (C1) in model 1, while in model 2 it is at 2.36 Å.

The fact that the C1–OG distance is longer in model 1 than in model 2 can be related to the Ser10⋯OG interaction, which is only present in model 1. In light of our results, it can be con- cluded that the interaction between Ser10 and the diphosphate group is key for the stabilization of the leaving group, because when this interaction is not present (model 2), the energy −1. barrier amounts to 54 kcal mol Thus, the fact that the reactant of model 1 exhibits the lowest energy barrier suggests that Ser10 could facilitate the cleavage of the glycosidic linkage by stabilizing the growing negative charge in the leaving group during the transfer of olivose. As a consequence, the C1–OG bond elongates and the C1–O5 bond shrinks in the reactant, which brings the reactant closer to the TS structure. Based on this evidence, we dis- carded further studies of model 2 and focused on model 1. The next step was a new evaluation of model 1, which involved the use of the QM2 zone, incorporating Ser10 in the QM fragment. Our results show that when Ser10 is part of the QM region (QM2 fragment), the energy barrier decreases to ∼29 kcal −1 lower in energy than the value mol −1). This (∼34 kcal mol obtained with the QM1 fragment energy change could be mainly related to the diﬀerent descrip- tion of the HS⋯OG interaction, which goes from 1.77 Å in the reactant (QM1 fragment) to 1.53 Å in the reactant modeled with the QM2 definition (Table S1†). The diﬀerent treatments used to describe the HS⋯OG inter- action reveal that this interaction is better described at the quantum level, giving account for a diminishing of 5 kcal −1 in the height of the energy barrier. Thus, we conclude mol that Ser10 is key to stabilizing the glycosidic bond cleavage through the HS⋯OG hydrogen bond. Consequently, the final QM partition used for the following electronic description of the process includes Ser10. Minimum energy path and catalytic mechanism

More specifically, in the reac- tant, the C1–O5 bond is of 1.40 Å, whereas the C1–OG and This journal is © The Royal Society of Chemistry 2021 HS⋯OG distances are 1.51 and 1.74 Å, respectively. These dis- tance values make it clear that the changes induced by the ⋯OG interaction are in the direction of the TS, in which the HS glycosidic bond is broken and the C1–O5 bond gains a partial double bond character (Fig. 5). In the TS, the nucleophile has been activated/deprotonated and it exists as a phenolate ion, which is positioned at 2.19 Å from the anomeric carbon of the olivosyl moiety (Fig. 5). Besides, the olivosyl moiety adopts a 4H3 half-chair conformation, according to the Cremer–Pople parameters (ϕ = 208° and θ = 52°); in this configuration, the C5–O5–C1–C2 group of atoms exhibits an almost coplanar arrangement, in which the C1–O5 bond undergoes a develop- ment of positive charge of 0.21 a.u. and a shortening of the C1–O5 distance by 0.09 Å (Fig. 5 and Table 1). Besides the structural characteristics, NBO ana- lysis also reveals a decrease in the p-character of the C1 atom and the formation of a new π bonding interaction between C1 and O5, in agreement with the expected Lewis structure of an oxocarbenium ion characterized by a rehybridization of the C1 atom from sp3 to sp2. At this point, the C1–OG distance lengthens up to 2.61 Å and the phenolate nucleophile is ready to attack, showing a C1–O8Tet distance of 2.19 Å. The phenol- ate character of Tet is revealed by a negative charge increase of 0.08 a.u. in the O8 atom (Table 1), in conjunction with the appearance of a π-orbital interaction on the C8–O8 bond of Tet. Given the development of negative charge in the O8 atom of Tet, the interactions provided by the enzyme environment become relevant for TS stabilization. negative charge on the nucleophile. The presence of this brid- ging water between Tet and Asp137 in O-LanGT2 seems to be the necessary due to the significance distance between Asp137 and the O8–H8 moiety of Tet (5 Å).33 As an additional piece of information, it is worth mentioning that a water molecule assisting in the activation of the nucleophile has been suggested for fucosyltransferase 1 (FUT1)23 from the GT37 family, which is also a metal ion-independent and inverting GT. This issue remains to be investigated, since to our knowl- edge, this proposal has not been evaluated by means of QM/ MM simulations. It is interesting to note that in the study of UGT1,20 the TS features the phenolic form of the nucleophile, and the O-site is at 2.61 Å from the anomeric carbon. This is 0.42 Å farther away than that observed in O-LanGT2 (2.19 Å). In UGT1, the nucleophilic activation of 3,4-dichlorophenol needs the His26/ Asp122 dyad, and His26 is essential to increase the nucleophi- lic character of the acceptor molecule. On the other hand, in O-LanGT2 the H2O/Asp137 pair activates the nucleophilic char- acter of Tet, and the water is crucial to stabilize the phenolate form of the nucleophile. The diﬀerent nucleophilic activation mechanisms could be the reason why UGT1 and O-LanGT2 exhibit the phenolic and phenolate forms of the acceptor sub- strate, respectively. Leaving group stabilization It was mentioned before that in metal ion-dependent GTs, the donor substrate is attached into the active site through electro- static interactions with a metal cofactor; the metal ion is part of the first shell of interactions of the diphosphate group and provides electrostatic stabilization to the growing negative charge on the diphosphate moiety. In the case of O-LanGT2, and other metal ion-independent GTs, it has been suggested that the positively charged side chains of amino acids may play this role.64 In this work, we deepen our analysis of the

Unbiased QM/MM calculations of the MEP, using the CPR algorithm, show that the reaction takes place through a SN2-like mechanism that features an oxocarbenium ion-like TS, in which the TDP-olivose breakage and the activation of the aromatic nucleophile have already occurred. The oxocarbenium ion adopts a 4H3 half-chair conformation, which helps bring the anomeric carbon (C1) closer to the phenolate moiety (nucleophile). Furthermore, the two models used in this study also made it possible to unravel the non-intuitive role of Ser10, which does not interact with any of the substrates in the X-ray structures, despite being identified as a key residue by mutagenesis experiments. Ser10 forms a strong hydrogen bonding interaction with the gly- cosidic oxygen (OG), which becomes stronger in the TS providing −1. These key details a delocalization energy of almost 38 kcal mol oﬀer a molecular interpretation of mutagenesis experiments, giving an explanation of the crucial role of Ser10.31 On the other hand, our QM/MM simulations also support the hypothesis that the water molecule (Wcat) can act as a shuttle between Asp137 and the phenol-like nucleophile. This network seems to be required given the substantial distance that separates the catalytic base and the acceptor substrate. Furthermore, our results suggest that the Wcat could help stabilize the growing negative charge in the TS through strong hydrogen bonding interactions with both the phenolate ion and aspartic acid.

Besides Ser10, the departure of the diphosphate group can be stabilized by residues such as Ser219, Arg220 and His283. This information also provides a molecular explanation of experiments, which revealed that the mutation of Ser219 for an alanine residue completely abolished the transferase activity of O-LanGT2. Additionally, the O2α⋯(HO3)Oli hydrogen −1, an bond provides a delocalization energy of 14 kcal mol intra-donor substrate interaction that resembles those found in other metal ion-independent GTs.21,22,28 Finally, the energy −1, a value that is similar barrier of the reaction is 24.9 kcal mol to those obtained for other metal ion-independent GTs, through QM/MM calculations.21,28 The results presented here are expected to help in under- standing the glycosylation of natural products. The impli- cations of this work could be of great interest not only for other inverting GTs, but also to unveil the C-glycosylation mechanism catalyzed by C-LanGT2, the chimeric variant of O-LanGT2, whose characteristics remain elusive.
